When I left the Army, and until I left the Army, I was 
never active in politics at all.

28:29.049 --> 28:36.077
In fact, I don't think I really, I always felt 
professional military people were outside the

28:29.049 --> 28:36.077
realm of politics. Now, the franchise, the vote's 
important, but I never really felt that I needed

28:42.361 --> 28:47.369
that, except wartime I liked to vote who was going 
to lead us. Who did you vote for then during the war?

28:50.354 --> 28:53.739
Well, I always voted for Roosevelt. I think he was a 
great war leader. And of course, at that time we had

28:57.245 --> 29:08.042
our great Sam Rayburn, Speaker of the House, and he 
and my father were friends, by the way. Sam Rayburn

29:08.502 --> 29:10.225
knew all the community leaders in his district.

29:15.963 --> 29:26.755
Anyway, I was not conscious of politics, ever 
really, until as I was winding up my military

29:15.963 --> 29:26.755
career. My last assignment was as chief of 
legislative liaison for the Army, which meant I

29:27.275 --> 29:38.507
was the senior liaison officer with the Congress.

29:40.377 --> 29:49.289
This, for the first time, gave me very close 
association and view of the federal government,

29:40.377 --> 29:49.289
and specifically the Congress.

29:52.513 --> 30:05.270
I'm still shocked to hear people in my present 
environment sound off about how lousy those

29:52.513 --> 30:05.270
members of Congress are, and they're all crooks. 
But I came away from that experience with a much

30:05.290 --> 30:09.135
enhanced regard for the total system of our 
government that our Constitution writers set up

30:10.330 --> 30:25.551
and a much more aware appreciation of the Congress 
as a as an institution and of the individuals in the

30:10.330 --> 30:25.551
Congress. They're among the most among the 
hardest working people I've ever known and for the

30:25.591 --> 30:38.749
most part extremely conscientious people.

30:38.769 --> 30:39.730
I have taken the the liberty to rebut some of these 
comments about our government and our

30:41.077 --> 30:46.863
congressmen. But, of course, in this country, we 
all have the right to say these things. We're very

30:50.867 --> 30:53.130
prone to do it because we hired them, you know. Oh, 
yeah, right. But I say if you threw a fishnet around

30:55.032 --> 31:05.223
100 guys in Kauffman and then took a look at each one 
of them individually, there'd be some of them

30:55.032 --> 31:05.223
you'd want to throw back. There's going to be two or 
three of them. that you'd rather not net. And I

31:14.350 --> 31:19.016
think it's about the same measure in Congress. We 
just hear so much about those who do stray and err

31:19.036 --> 31:27.065
and show up to be crooks or immoral. There are not 
many of them. No. Were you ever a member of a

31:31.891 --> 31:34.434
political party then? Well, when I did leave the 
Army and had that experience with the Congress, I

31:34.554 --> 31:41.222
felt very strongly that Every citizen should get 
involved because politics is defined as the art of

31:41.371 --> 31:49.358
governing, and we're supposed to govern 
ourselves. If we can't contribute to it, we have no

31:49.578 --> 31:59.327
right to make that criticism or complain about 
conditions as they are. But I became a Democrat

31:59.547 --> 32:11.158
because, well, you might say my heritage was that, 
and I'd always felt associated with it, although I

31:59.547 --> 32:11.158
was never active before. sometimes I wonder and I 
guess we all do

32:11.543 --> 32:39.627
whether I should say I'm a Democrat or join the 
Republican Party because on some issues I'm very

32:11.543 --> 32:39.627
much on that side other issues I think my party that 
I've chosen to support is correct I basically feel

32:11.543 --> 32:39.627
that It's not right to call yourself an 
independent because we do have a two-party system

32:41.193 --> 32:49.182
and I think it's very important to us. And as a 
matter of fact, I regret now that the Republicans

32:49.202 --> 33:01.956
didn't gain control of the House of 
Representatives so that they would control the

32:49.202 --> 33:01.956
White House and the Senate and the House. Just as I 
felt that while Mr. Carter was not my choice, and

33:10.302 --> 33:15.548
among the nominees to be president or candidate 
for the Democratic Party. Once he was nominated,

33:16.829 --> 33:28.803
as far as I was concerned, he looked acceptable, 
and I supported him, and I knew it was impossible to

33:16.829 --> 33:28.803
have a Republican Congress, so no one really, it 
just makes sense, let's get one party

33:16.829 --> 33:28.803
responsible. And if they don't hack it, then the 
other party has the absolute right to be elected.

33:36.121 --> 33:37.423
to have their hand in it. Well, the Republicans 
almost did, and I wish they had, because then

33:37.443 --> 33:47.097
they'd have full responsibility for the 
leadership of the government. So in 1976, then,

33:47.157 --> 33:52.425
you supported Jimmy Carter, and then in 1980, you 
supported Ronald Reagan? That's right. I think

33:53.486 --> 33:56.911
Mr. Carter failed. The reason I feel that one party 
feels so strongly one party should control the

33:56.931 --> 34:02.820
federal government We had two terms of, well, Mr. 
President Eisenhower had a Democratic Congress.

34:10.771 --> 34:12.874
President Nixon had a Democratic Congress. I saw 
President Nixon's administration at first hand.

34:17.380 --> 34:30.299
And I think that division is very bad for us, that 
division of responsibility, with one party

34:17.380 --> 34:30.299
responsible for making the laws and another party 
responsible for carrying them out. And look at

34:30.319 --> 34:34.545
what's going on in the House of Representatives 
today. foot dragging in me, or simply to express an

34:35.133 --> 34:41.964
individuality of view. And I think Democrats are 
good people, but I think it's time that the

34:42.385 --> 34:51.279
Republicans run this thing and be responsible for 
it. Sure. For the good and the bad. Yes, sir. I'm

34:57.338 --> 34:58.800
somewhat confused then. Would you say that you're 
a conservative or a moderate or a liberal? How

35:02.445 --> 35:22.470
would you define your personal... Well, I don't 
think that's very hard to do because

35:02.445 --> 35:22.470
if you just look at the last ten years since I've 
been, shall we say, exercising my franchise to

35:02.445 --> 35:22.470
vote and participate in politics...

35:24.678 --> 35:27.201
the color of conservatives has changed a great 
deal.

35:30.105 --> 35:46.005
And on the other hand, liberals, we don't see near 
as much evidence of the liberals today as we did two

35:30.105 --> 35:46.005
Congresses ago, when we swept in a whole huge 
numbers of young liberals. I don't think that's a

35:47.387 --> 35:48.789
fair way to do it. I think that the conditions in the 
country change, and I think the things that are

35:54.580 --> 36:23.440
important to me are very important to me is of 
course first of all national security you would

35:54.580 --> 36:23.440
expect that given my career and so I spend a great 
deal of time excuse this throat I don't know why I'm

35:54.580 --> 36:23.440
getting all tangled up here well let me finish this

35:54.580 --> 36:23.440
I am a great conservative when it comes to national 
security because I think that we're gambling with

36:24.331 --> 36:46.914
the security of this nation to adopt a strategy as 
did

36:24.331 --> 36:46.914
President Kennedy and Johnson with Robert 
McNamara, Secretary of Defense, that being equal

36:24.331 --> 36:46.914
is good enough. I know it's awfully hard to 
