37:06.194 --> 37:12.964
international relations are, of course, allied 
to this very, very closely. And so international

37:14.867 --> 37:18.672
affairs are of great interest to me. And I don't 
know what's a conservative in international

37:20.272 --> 37:25.458
affairs or what's a liberal. But if being 
conservative is to resist the very thought of any

37:26.419 --> 37:37.492
further communist encroachment into the Western 
hemisphere, then I'm a conservative. The people

37:39.034 --> 37:48.625
who say let the Central Americans determine their 
own fate down there, I've served in Latin America,

37:39.034 --> 37:48.625
and I know how these are determined. And I think 
we're stupid if we let that happen. We've got to

37:52.144 --> 38:00.292
influence it, and we've got to influence it in our 
favor for our future as a nation and for the future

37:52.144 --> 38:00.292
of our people. Somewhere in here, economics 
stands

38:01.533 --> 38:10.421
right up alongside these things. In fact, they're 
the base from which the strength flows for

38:10.481 --> 38:17.127
national security and an effective foreign 
policy. So are you conservative or liberal on

38:17.917 --> 38:20.239
economics? So on economics, I'm liberal in the 
sense of opening trade. I don't believe in

38:27.305 --> 38:33.631
tariffs, barriers.

38:36.093 --> 38:45.041
I really don't believe in subsidies for 
international trade, but that's very common

38:36.093 --> 38:45.041
throughout the world. What about subsidies for 
farm products? I

38:47.600 --> 38:53.950
don't believe in subsidies as such for farm 
products. I would rather, and I believe most

38:54.090 --> 39:13.860
people in agriculture, and I'm just dabbling in 
it, would much rather see a free up of the markets

38:54.090 --> 39:13.860
plus the knowledge that they can get a federal 
federally guaranteed loan if they just looked too

39:14.195 --> 39:23.424
bad on the books for the bankers to say, I can't do it 
because bank regulations won't let me. I think

39:24.645 --> 39:26.126
most farmers would be happy with that. So I guess 
I'm

39:27.167 --> 39:34.414
a moderate, I guess, because somewhere in the 
middle is the average of my views. I only forgot one

39:34.494 --> 39:35.615
thing. That's social legislation or social 
programs. Do you consider yourself a moderate? I

39:40.660 --> 39:42.902
would say I'm a moderate on social legislation. 
legislation or social programs. I think we've

39:46.387 --> 39:47.909
gone far overboard. But I think that, for example, 
I think Social Security is a fine thing. It's a

39:54.299 --> 39:57.944
must.

39:59.827 --> 40:05.916
But I believe also that Mr. Reagan is correct, that 
he's gotten all out of focus. It's become many

40:06.717 --> 40:11.404
things other than the intended floor for the 
person who has to quit work or retire. It's become

40:15.160 --> 40:17.443
an education vehicle for the kids. It's become a 
disability compensation program. It's become a

40:22.087 --> 40:31.397
very, very expensive thing. Now, on other social 
programs, I believe that there should be some kind

40:31.417 --> 40:41.847
of a medical insurance program. that protects 
every family or every individual from that

40:44.307 --> 40:49.054
disastrous illness. But to be able to go to your 
doctor because you don't feel well and have the

40:51.318 --> 40:57.328
government pay for it, I don't believe in that. I do 
believe because we certainly practice this in the

40:59.251 --> 41:09.707
military, but preventive health measures are 
much less expensive than that. Corrective, just

41:09.856 --> 41:14.583
like preventive maintenance is better than 
mechanics repairs on your automobile. But

41:15.764 --> 41:17.967
somewhere we've gone too far in this. Medicaid, 
Medicare, and so forth. I think it's too

41:23.215 --> 41:26.379
expensive. Well, we're ready to start A&M, but 
first we're going to get some water for you. Now,

41:31.186 --> 41:35.091
let's continue. And I wanted to know if... Why did 
you decide to go to A&M? Here you have an older

41:41.598 --> 41:45.404
brother, one going to TCU, and one going to A&M. Why 
A&M? Probably because my older brother went there

41:48.348 --> 41:56.400
and was going there, and I had some good friends. 
One of my closest friends went to A&M. He was ahead

42:00.866 --> 42:05.833
of me a year in high school.

42:07.872 --> 42:15.764
And to tell you the truth, I didn't study the field 
of universities available to me like youngsters

42:07.872 --> 42:15.764
do now. Yeah. A&M attracted my attention, and it 
seemed just the place I ought to go. There were no

42:25.379 --> 42:27.922
other alternatives then, really? I never really 
considered them. And as a matter of fact, I had to

42:29.305 --> 42:36.175
wait a year after graduating high school before 
I'd go to A&M. And then I wasn't sure I was going to be

42:37.268 --> 42:40.231
able to enroll that fall. All of a sudden, Dad says, 
well, that's what's important. You better get on

42:45.255 --> 42:46.456
down to A&M. This is like a week before school 
started. So this friend took me down, and there I

42:48.958 --> 42:53.122
was. That year I was out of school, I should 
mention, was a very valuable year to me. Because in

43:00.989 --> 43:05.533
those days, see, we were graduating high school at 
the age of 17. We only had 11. grades in school. And I

43:11.249 --> 43:15.153
couldn't go to school for financial reasons. And 
so I stayed out. And that was the first year that

43:17.576 --> 43:26.587
Coffman High School offered what they call 
postgraduate courses, which I guess they now call

43:17.576 --> 43:26.587
continuing education. And so I enrolled to keep 
active. And I took bookkeeping,

43:31.413 --> 43:38.241
vocational agriculture, Typing, I guess that was 
it. And at the same time, you were living out here

43:44.752 --> 43:47.617
helping your father on the ranch? Living out here 
helping my dad. As a matter of fact, that cotton gin

43:49.220 --> 43:56.852
down there you saw, old building, that cotton gin 
was operating. And dad hurt himself in that cotton

43:56.872 --> 44:01.760
gin. He had an injury to his knee, and he was just 
laid up. And I had to drop out of post-graduate

44:06.318 --> 44:08.561
school. And I actually ran that cotton gin as 
manager and chief honcho for the rest of the

44:09.422 --> 44:18.072
season, about two and a half months. And that was a 
very good experience. I was responsible for

44:20.715 --> 44:31.187
keeping the books, collecting, paying the 
customer for his seed, and seeing that everybody

44:20.715 --> 44:31.187
was there for work, and we had what we needed and 
everything. Very fine experience. And that's why

44:32.088 --> 44:35.532
I mentioned to you earlier that I probably got more 
education that year than any other year of my

44:36.035 --> 44:38.718
schooling. That was a lot of responsibility for a 
17-year-old. Very good experience. And how many

44:43.304 --> 44:46.107
people did you have working for you then? The 
minimum crew down there was four more, four

44:47.469 --> 44:54.518
additional people, five additional people. You 
had a man on the section, you had a fireman, you had a

44:54.538 --> 45:00.405
gym stand operator, and you had two people up in the 
press room. So you were at 17. You were in charge of

45:03.802 --> 45:05.684
five of them. Of course, I grew up with that cotton 
gin. I worked in there every year until we went to

45:07.667 --> 45:14.317
school. In those days, too, we started school late 
